enerated through the following components:\\n\\n1. **TimeoutException Definition**: Located in `apache/kafka` at `clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/errors/TimeoutException.java`. This class extends RetriableException and is the exception thrown when a request times out.\\n\\n2. **Record Batch Expiration Logic**: The expiration mechanism involves two key files:\\n   - `apache/kafka` at `clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/producer/internals/RecordAccumulator.java` contains the `expiredBatches(long now)` method (line 465) which identifies batches that have exceeded the delivery timeout. It iterates through all topic partitions and their queued batches, checking if each batch has exceeded the delivery timeout using `batch.hasReachedDeliveryTimeout(deliveryTimeoutMs, now)`.\\n   - `apache/kafka` at `clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/producer/internals/Sender.java` contains the `sendProducerData(long now)` method (line 357) which calls `accumulator.expiredBatches(now)` (line 407) and then iterates through the expired batches. For each expired batch, it constructs the error message \\\"Expiring {recordCount} record(s) for {topicPartition}:{timeElapsed} ms has passed since batch creation\\\" and throws a TimeoutException (lines 416-418).\\n\\n3. **Configuration Constant**: The `delivery.timeout.ms` configuration is defined in `apache/kafka` at `clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/producer/ProducerConfig.java`. The constant `DELIVERY_TIMEOUT_MS_CONFIG` (line 165) represents the \\\"delivery.timeout.ms\\\" configuration key. This configuration defines an upper bound on the time to report success or failure after a call to send(), controlling when record batches will expire.\"\n}\n",
